A prominent civil rights advocacy group, Human Rights Writers Association of Nigeria (HURIWA) has appealed to President Muhammadu Buhari to immediately activate mechanisms to unravel the role of fifth columnists undermining the goals and gains of the current war on terror. The rights group made the call in a statement jointly signed by the National Coordinator, Comrade Emmanuel Onwubiko and the National Media Affairs Director, Miss Zainab Yusuf, yesterday in Abuja. The group said the recent killings and losses suffered by innocent citizens in the hands of armed terrorists might not have occurred if these daredevil dubious saboteurs were stopped. “From hatching and executing their diabolical plots and scheming against the hierarchies of the nation’s security forces and against the President and Commander-In-Chief of the Armed Forces of the Federal Republic of Nigeria. “This is so much a norm that it is said our laws are better observed in the breach. Government and the public cannot be on different levels of operation and expect to have a same society. “More so that the twin evils of terror and insecurity are largely by-products of people-government interaction and to a large extent a measure of the state of health of the relationship. This makes this discourse a most relevant one at this time of our national life,” it stated. On the controversial detention of Jalingo Agba, a journalist who has been detained for about six months,  HURIWA said he should not be charged with any criminal offences for holding the state government accountable. HURIWA, however, frowned at the Cross River State governor, Ben Ayade for holding Jalingo Agba prisoner against court order. It further called on Nigerians to support war against terror, even as it also called for a halt to the release of the so-called repentant Boko Haram terrorists into the society.